05140nam a22006375i 9780226823393DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226823393  a(DE-B1597)641554  a(OCoLC)1350570501  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aML3877b.B37 2023 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a781.1/7223/eng/20220428  aLH 658292rvk0(DE-625)rvk/94562:131131 aBarrett, G Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aExperimenting the Human :bArt, Music, and the Contemporary Posthuman /cG Douglas Barrett. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b4 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction Music in a Wired Brain -- t1 The Brain at Work: Cognitive Labor, the Posthuman Brain, and Alvin Lucier’s Music for Solo Performer -- t2 “How We Were Never Posthuman”: Techniques of the Posthuman Body in Pamela Z’s Voci -- t3 “The Catastrophe of Technology”: Posthuman Automata and Nam June Paik’s Robot K-456 -- t4 Deep (Space) Listening: SETI, Moonbounce, and Pauline Oliveros’s Echoes from the Moon -- t5 Engendering the Digital: Digitality and the Posthuman Hand in Laetitia Sonami’s Lady’s Glove -- t6 The Last Invention: Recursion, Recordings, and Yasunao Tone’s AI Deviation -- tConclusion Music after Extinction -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn engaging argument about what experimental music can tell us about being human. In Experimenting the Human, G Douglas Barrett argues that experimental music speaks to the contemporary posthuman, a condition in which science and technology decenter human agency amid the uneven temporality of postwar global capitalism. Time moves forward for some during this period, while it seems to stand still or even move backward for others. Some say we’re already posthuman, while others endure the extended consequences of never having been considered fully human in the first place. Experimental music reflects on this state, Barrett contends, through its interdisciplinary involvements in postwar science, technology, and art movements. Rather than pursuing the human's beyond, experimental music addresses the social and technological conditions that support such a pursuit. Barrett locates this tendency of experimentalism throughout its historical entanglements with cybernetics, and in his intimate analysis of Alvin Lucier’s neurofeedback music, Pamela Z’s BodySynth performances, Nam June Paik’s musical robotics, Pauline Oliveros’s experiments with radio astronomy, and work by Laetitia Sonami, Yasunao Tone, and Jerry Hunt. Through a unique meeting of music studies, media theory, and art history, Experimenting the Human provides fresh insights into what it means to be human.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and music. 0aAvant-garde (Music). 0aMusic and technology. 0aMusicxSocial aspects. 0aPosthumanism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aexperimental music, posthumanism, cybernetics, contemporary art, indeterminacy, media studies, music technology, artificial intelligence, postwar era, political economy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023z978311131812708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022